</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>SB1286:v98#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="SB1286"/><meta name="dc:title" content="SB &#xA;              1286-&#xA;                AMENDED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Amended
               IN </span><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Senate
              </span> <span style="text-transform: uppercase">April 15, 2026</span><br/></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 1286</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Richardson<br/>(Coauthors: Senators Allen, Blakespear, McGuire, Strickland, Weber Pierson, and Wiener)<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 20, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act to add<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> and repeal</i></font> Section 425.4<font color="#B30000"><strike> to</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> of</i></font> the Government Code, relating to state government. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SB 1286, as amended, Richardson.
                          <font color="#B30000"><strike>State pinniped. </strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>California State Library: study: state pinniped.</i></font></span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the state flag and the state’s emblems, including, among other things, the California Grizzly Bear as the state animal, the California gray whale as the state marine mammal, and the Pacific leatherback sea turtle as the state marine reptile.<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Existing law establishes the California State Library within the state government and vests control of the library to the State Librarian. Existing law authorizes the California State Library to serve as the central reference and research library for the departments of state government and maintain adequate legislative reference and research library services for the Legislature.</i></font></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>This bill would establish the California sea lion as the official state pinniped. The bill would also make related findings and declarations.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the California State Library to conduct a study, in consultation with the public, on the best candidate for the official state pinniped. The bill would require the California State Library, on or before January 1, 2028, to submit a report to the Legislature with the California State Library’s recommendations based on the study, as provided. The bill would repeal these provisions on January 1, 2032.</div></i></font></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase"><font color="#B30000"><strike>NO</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>YES</i></font></span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.9455939291470151"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>SECTION 1.</i></font></h3> <font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Section 425.4 is added to the Government Code, to read:</i></font></div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i></i></font><div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div id="id_7DA6E51D-E122-442F-A160-7AC83BED6F28"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">425.4.</h6> (a) The California State Library shall conduct a study, in consultation with the public, on the best candidate for the official state pinniped.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) On or before January 1, 2028, the California State Library shall submit a report to the Legislature with the California State Library’s recommendations based on the study conducted pursuant to subdivision (a).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) A report to be submitted pursuant to paragraph (1) shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) This section shall be repealed on January 1, 2032, pursuant to Section 10231.5.</div></p></div></div></i></font></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_B182E619-B159-46B3-8EA3-8995107267C9"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SECTION 1.</caml:Num><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>Pinnipeds are fin- or flipper-footed marine mammals that have front and rear flippers; the California sea lion is a member of the “eared seal” family.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(b)<span class="EnSpace"/>California sea lions are found along the shore from California to Mexico, including Baja and Tres Marias Islands, in the Galapagos Islands, and in the southern Sea of Japan. They generally live along coastlines but have been found in rivers along the northern Pacific coast. California sea lions often congregate on man-made structures such as jetties, piers, offshore buoys, and oil platforms.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>California sea lions have been known to assemble at the mouths of freshwater rivers where there is a steady supply of fish. They also feed on cephalopods, anchovies, herring, Pacific whiting, rockfish, hake, salmon, squid, and octopuses.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>The California sea lion, once in severe decline, has rebounded and is abundant today because of the federal Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972 (Public Law 92-522).</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(e)<span class="EnSpace"/>It is the intent of the Legislature that this recognition helps provide additional protections as California sea lions face a rapidly changing environment.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:BillSection><caml:BillSection id="id_1F97B91B-0628-4C0D-84A2-4C7F1E9010E6"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SEC. 2.</caml:Num><caml:ActionLine action="IS_ADDED" xlink:href="urn:caml:codes:GOV:caml#xpointer(%2Fcaml%3ALawDoc%2Fcaml%3ACode%2F%2Fcaml%3ALawSection%5Bcaml%3ANum%3D'425.4'%5D)" xlink:label="fractionType: LAW_SECTION" xlink:type="locator">Section 425.4 is added to the <caml:DocName>Government Code</caml:DocName>, to read:</caml:ActionLine><caml:Fragment><caml:LawSection id="id_ECA4F315-4E0E-438F-A8AC-973D4D431A41"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>425.4.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_00F26B96-047C-4B3F-9E2F-3F00371DEADB"><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The California sea lion (Zalophus californianus) is the official state pinniped.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></caml:Fragment></caml:BillSection></strike></font></div></div></body></html>
